Mariupol (, ; ; also ; ;
) is a port city in southeastern Ukraine, on the shore of the Sea of Azov, near the mouth of the Kalmius. Administratively, Mariupol is a city of regional significance within the Donetsk Oblast (province), though since February 2015 it has been under the control of pro-Russian separatists as the capital of the self-proclaimed Donetsk People's Republic. As of 1 January 2022, the city had a population of 431,859, making it the ninth-most populous city in Ukraine.
The city was founded in 1778 as a Russian military fortification on the site of the Zaporizhian Cossack settlement of Voznesenske. It was renamed Mariupol in 1779 after Maria Feodorovna, wife of Emperor Paul I of Russia. During the 19th century, Mariupol developed into an important industrial centre, particularly for the production of iron and steel. In the early 20th century, the city became a major hub for the export of coal from the Donets Basin. During World War II, Mariupol was occupied by Nazi Germany from October 1941 to September 1943. The city was heavily damaged during the war, and much of its industrial infrastructure was destroyed. After the war, Mariupol experienced a period of rapid growth and development, particularly in the 1960s and 1970s. However, the city's economy began to decline in the late 1980s and early 1990s, due to the collapse of the Soviet Union and the subsequent economic crisis in Ukraine.
In 2014, following the Euromaidan protests and the ousting of President Viktor Yanukovych, tensions between pro-Russian and pro-Ukrainian groups in Mariupol escalated. In May 2014, pro-Russian separatists seized control of the city and declared it part of the Donetsk People's Republic, a self-proclaimed state that is not recognized by any other country. Since then, Mariupol has been the site of frequent clashes between Ukrainian government forces and pro-Russian separatists. In June 2014, Ukrainian forces launched an offensive to retake the city, but were repelled by the separatists. In January 2015, a ceasefire agreement was reached between the Ukrainian government and the separatists, which led to a reduction in fighting in Mariupol. However, sporadic clashes continue to occur in the city, and the situation remains tense.
